@Node Introduction "BindNamesII/Introduction"

 @{u}@{b}Introduction@{uu}@{ub}

 Quite a while ago, Dave Haynie wrote this really nice assign utility called
BindNames. However, this program lacked OS 2.0 support (indeed, it works
with OS 1.3 and up). There have been a few updates (not by Dave Haynie),
that addressed a part of this, namely the multi-drawer assign (Assign <...>
ADD). The last one also added an "automount" feature, and I started using
this version a while ago.

 When I installed XFH (again! :), a problem occured. I had an assign
relative to this XFH volume, and it seemed like XFH didn't start up quickly
enough for BindNames to be able to do the assign. Since this assign was a
part of the AmigaGuide search path, this quickly got a bit annoying. In an
attempt to solve this problem, I decided to make my own version of
BindNames, with full OS 2.0 support (indeed, it requires OS 2.0). I also
added a couple of other features on the way. The result is this program,
called BindNamesII (since I couldn't think of anything better! :).  And as
I hoped, the problem went away. :)

 Note: BindNamesII should work fine with all name files for the original
BindNames. The assign ADDs are specified a bit different, causing problems
with files using this feature in the later versions of BindNames.

 Currently it does lack one feature in BindNames: The ability to re-assign
the system to a different disk. I can add this, if needed. On the other
hand, it wouldn't be that difficult to do by hand.. :)

@EndNode


@Node License "BindNamesII/License"

 @{u}@{b}License@{uu}@{ub}

 This program is release under the GNU General Public License (version 2 or
later). Please see the file @{"COPYING" Link COPYING/Main} for details.

 Although released under the GPL, I would appriciate if you don't release
modified versions yourself; I would rather like you to send me your
changes, so that I can incorporate them in a new version. This to prevent
having several different strains of the program, which might confuse the
users.

@EndNode


@Node Usage "BindNamesII/Usage"

 @{u}@{b}Usage@{uu}@{ub}

 BindNamesII have the following template:

 @{"DRAWER" Link DRAWER},@{"TEST/S" Link TEST},@{"VERBOSE/S" Link VERBOSE},@{"QUIET/S" Link QUIET},@{"PATHADDCHAR/K" Link PATHADDCHAR},@{"PATHSTART/K" Link PATHSTART}:

 Simply place it somewere you like in 'S:User-Startup' (or if you are a bit
daring, in 'S:Startup-Sequence').


 @{b}Hint for advanced users:@{ub}

 If you would like to replace your 'Ram:' with StatRam or VDisk, then do
something like this, early in your Startup-Sequence:

   Assign Ram: DISMOUNT
   BindNamesII QUIET

 The 'Ram:' replacement should be defined in 'Devs:MountList' (or if you
have OS 2.1+, you can place it in the file 'Sys:Storage/DosDrivers/Ram').
You don't need to assign 'Env:' anywhere (some Mount versions asks for
'Env:'), since such volume requesters are disabled when BindNamesII is
running the Mount command.

@EndNode


@Node DRAWER "BindNamesII/Usage/DRAWER"
@Toc Usage

 @{u}@{b}DRAWER@{uu}@{ub}

 This is the drawer where BindNamesII looks for the name files to read. All
files in this drawer are read and processed (any drawers are ignored).
Default is 'Sys:Names'.

@EndNode


@Node TEST "BindNamesII/Usage/TEST"
@Toc Usage

 @{u}@{b}TEST@{uu}@{ub}

 This is for testing purposes; If specified, then nothing is actually done,
but BindNamesII tries to resolve all links, assuming that all assigns and
makedirs are successfull, while all mounts (to unknown volumes) are not
successfull. This way you can see if you have any unresolved links or not.
See @{"TARGET" Link TARGET} for more information.

@EndNode


@Node VERBOSE "BindNamesII/Usage/VERBOSE"
@Toc Usage

 @{u}@{b}VERBOSE@{uu}@{ub}

 If specified, then BindNamesII will print a message for each attempted
mount, and display a list of all assigns made that were successfull. The
list is very similar to the one produced by Assign.

@EndNode


@Node QUIET "BindNamesII/Usage/QUIET"
@Toc Usage

 @{u}@{b}QUIET@{uu}@{ub}

 Normally BindNamesII prints all unresolved links when finished. If this
option is specified, then this will not happen. Other errors are printed as
usual.

@EndNode


@Node PATHADDCHAR "BindNamesII/Usage/PATHADDCHAR"
@Toc Usage

 @{u}@{b}PATHADDCHAR@{uu}@{ub}

 Here you can specify the path separator that should be used with the
@{"PATHADD" Link "PATHADD"} option. If you don't have PathHandler (or something similar),
you'll probably not have any use for it. Default is "|".

@EndNode


@Node PATHSTART "BindNamesII/Usage/PATHSTART"
@Toc Usage

 @{u}@{b}PATHSTART@{uu}@{ub}

 Another PathHandler special. Here you can specify the name of your
PathHandler device. Default is 'Path:'.

@Endnode


@Node Files "BindNamesII/Name files"

 @{u}@{b}Name files@{uu}@{ub}

 The format of the assign files are quite simple. Place one assign on each
line, using the following template:

 @{"NAME/A" Link NAME},@{"TARGET/A/M" Link TARGET},@{"ALIAS/K" Link ALIAS},@{"PRI=PRIORITY/K/N" Link PRIORITY},@{"DEFER/S" Link DEFER},@{"PATH/S" Link PATH},@{"ADD/S" Link ADD},
@{"PATHADD/S" Link PATHADD}

 This is very similar to the normal Assign command, with a few extras.

 You can enter comments, by placing a ";" or "#" char at the beginning of a
line.

 @{i}Note: @{ui}Empty lines are not accepted!

@EndNode


@Node NAME "BindNamesII/Name files/NAME"
@Toc Files

 @{u}@{b}NAME@{uu}@{ub}

 This is the name of the assign, with a colon at the end (see below for
exceptions). If it contains spaces, quote it. This argument must be
specified. You don't need to specify a colon at the end, but for
consistency with Assign, it is a good idea to do it anyway.

 As of version 1.3 of BindNamesII, there is a special assign, called
"CMDPATH". If that one is specified, @{i}without @{ui}a trailing colon, then the
@{"TARGET" Link TARGET} drawers will replace/be added to the current command search path.
This way you can easily have both assigns and path commands in the same
file (or at least the same drawer).

 All special options related to assigns are ignored if this special name is
used. Only the @{"PATHADD" Link PATHADD}, @{"PRIORITY" Link PRIORITY} and @{"ADD" Link ADD} options are considered. The paths
are added after all assigns have been made.

 Because of this special 'assign', another good reason to use colon at the
end of normal assigns is to make it easier to see the difference between
them. Also, if you want a normal assign, called "CMDPATH", simply specify
it with a colon at the end.

@EndNode


@Node TARGET "BindNamesII/Name files/TARGET"
@Toc Files

 @{u}@{b}TARGET@{uu}@{ub}

 The target of the assign (or the path, if the name is 'CMDPATH'). Any
number of targets may be specified (unless the @{"PATH" Link PATH} or @{"DEFER" Link DEFER} option have
been specified), but at least one must be specified.

 If the same @{"NAME" Link NAME} is found on two lines, the targets for the second line
will be added to the first @{"NAME" Link NAME}; it doesn't replace the first definition.
This makes it almost trivial to add assigns to e.g. 'S:'.

 To force a target to appear first (this is indeed usefule sometimes), even
if not found first, put a "/" char first in the name. Note that specifying
"/" for several targets will cause problems in the sense that the last
target found with the "/" char will be placed first.

 Admittedly, this might look a bit weird. But if you don't put a slash
("/") at the end of each path (there is no need), it won't be that bad.

 As of version 1.3 of BindNamesII, there is a more flexible way of
specifying "search order". See @{"PRIORITY" Link PRIORITY} for more information about this.
The "/" char always have a higher priority than what can be specified with
PRIORITY.


 @{u}Notes:@{uu}

 If a target drawer doesn't exist, BindNamesII will try to create all the
needed drawers. This way, you don't need to create e.g. 'Ram:T', or even
'Ram:Foo/Bar'.

 Also, if the target volume doesn't exist, BindNamesII will try to mount
it before giving up. This mount is done after all assigns to volumes that
exists are done.

@EndNode


@Node ALIAS "BindNamesII/Name files/ALIAS"
@Toc Files

 @{u}@{b}ALIAS@{uu}@{ub}

 A special one for all users of PathHandler (part of WShell 2.0). If
specified, the comment of the assign will be set to the string specified here.
For more information about this feature, check your WShell manual.

 If more than one ALIAS is encountered for an assign, then the first one
encountered is used.

@EndNode


@Node PRIORITY "BindNamesII/Name files/PRIORITY"
@Toc Files

 @{u}@{b}PRIORITY@{uu}@{ub}

 Synonym: PRI

 Here you can specify the "priority" for the currently specified targets.
To set different priority for different targets, specify them on separate
lines. However, this shouldn't be needed, as the internal order within each
line (and group of targets) will always be retained.

 If several target groups have the same priority, targets found later will
be added to the end. Targets are ordered with decreasing priority value.
The "/" char in front of a target always have higher priority than what can
be specified here. Accepted range is 127 to -128. Default is 0.

@EndNode


@Node DEFER "BindNamesII/Name files/DEFER"
@Toc Files

 @{u}@{b}DEFER@{uu}@{ub}

 If specified, then this assign will not be resolved until referenced for the
first time. Useful for volumes that aren't available during startup. Note that
you can't have several targets for this assign.

@EndNode


@Node PATH "BindNamesII/Name files/PATH"
@Toc Files

 @{u}@{b}PATH@{uu}@{ub}

 If specified, then this assign will be resolved each time it is
referenced. Mostly useful for assigns to floppies. Note that you can't have
several targets for this assign.

@EndNode


@Node ADD "BindNamesII/Name files/ADD"
@Toc Files

 @{u}@{b}ADD@{uu}@{ub}

 If specified, then this assign will be added to any already existing
assign. If not specified, then the assign will completely replace any
earlier assign. Perhaps not that useful, but this way you don't need to
re-assign e.g. 'S:'.

 This option works just the same for command path lines (assign called
"CMDPATH"). If specified, the old path will be left untouched.

 @{i}Note: @{ui}The previous assign that already existed will not be listed by the
@{"VERBOSE" Link "VERBOSE"} switch, since it only shows the assigns acually made by
BindNamesII. Also, any new targets will be added after the already existing
ones, regardless of specified @{"PRIORITY" Link PRIORITY}.

@EndNode


@Node PATHADD "BindNamesII/Name files/PATHADD"
@Toc Files

 @{u}@{b}PATHADD@{uu}@{ub}

 Another PathHandler special. If specified, and there is a @{"TARGET" Link TARGET} relative
to 'Path:' for this @{"NAME" Link NAME} (in either the current or another line), then all
assigns will be stored as a 'Path:' assign. Otherwise the assign will be
added to any previous one, as normal.

 @{i}Note: @{ui}I'm not sure this is the best way to do it. Should BindNamesII perhaps
always use a 'Path:' relative assign, regardless if there is one already or
not? @{"Comments" Link "Author"} are appriciated.

@EndNode


