@Node Source "BindNamesII/Source"

 @{u}@{b}Source@{uu}@{ub}

 Since it was a while ago I released a program with its source, I decided
to do it with this one. To make sure the program remains free, I released
in under the @{"GNU General Public License" Link "License"}.

 In the archive you can find the complete source for BindNamesII. It was
written using the DICE compiler. You probably need to make a few changes to
get it compile with others.

 Since the assignment process isn't trivial (but it isn't that complicated
either! :), I thought I should outline what happens in the program.

 After the general initializations, argument parsing etc, the specified
drawer is scanned. Each file is read in, and one AssignNode is allocated
for each assign line found. The AllocAssignNode() function handles the node
allocation, and also takes care of checking for any previous assign with
the same name. If there was one, the new PathNodes (each PathNode contains
information about one target drawer, and any AssignNode it refers to) will
be added to the AssignNode. Otherwise a new AssignNode is created.

 After all files have been read, the PrepareAssignList() function is
called. This function sets up all relationships between the AssignNodes,
checks which assigns that can be done at once, which assigns that needs
another assign to be done first, and which assigns that refers to "unknown"
volumes (all AssignNodes that - either directly or indirectly - refers to
unknown volumes are called stray nodes). @{"PATH" Link PATH} or @{"DEFER" Link DEFER} assigns are not
checked for unknown volumes, since they don't need to be resolved directly.
It also checks for loop assigns and merges any @{"PathHandler" Link PATHADD} assigns that
should be merged.

 Now the assign process can be started. This is handled by the AssignList()
function. First we assign all nodes that can be assigned directly (nodes
that have other nodes as parents are delayed, by putting them at the end of
the list again). Stray nodes are moved to a separate list for later
processing. After the first round of assignments, all stray nodes are
examined for unknown volumes, and the program tries to mount the needed
volumes. Finally, the remaining nodes are assigned.

 Note: CMDPATH assigns are treated a little differently. In
PrepareAssignList(), such nodes are largely ignored. Only the "/" and
@{"PATHADD" Link PATHADD} handling is done.

 Note: The AssignList() function handles the printing of assignments (both
those that were successful that those that weren't), and frees the
AssignNodes.

@EndNode


@Node History "BindNamesII/Program history"

 @{u}@{b}Program history@{uu}@{ub}

 @{u}Version 1.0@{uu}

   Release date: 30 November 1994

   Ę Initial release.

 @{u}Version 1.1@{uu}

   Release date: 1 February 1995

   Ę "PATHADD adding" didn't always work. Sometimes it didn't allocate
     enough memory, causing crashes.

   Ę The directory creator could trash memory (stack overflow), if a
     destination path was improperly specified.

   Ę Oops! The @{"QUIET" Link QUIET} option wasn't implemented! Caused a few problems.. :)

   Ę Assigns relative to an assign that needed a target to be mounted could
     be made at the wrong time. You didn't get it? ;) An example to clarify
     (from my system):

     Help:    Text:Guide
     Text:    Path:Work:Text|User:Text

     The Path: volume needs to be mounted, and because of this, the "parent
     assigns" handling for Help: wasn't done. Thus, BindNamesII (usually)
     tried to assign Help: before it had assigned Text:.

   Ę A few other minor cleanups.

   Ę Did some changes to make it compile with Gcc. Doesn't always work.
     E.g., optimization must be on, or a weird error occur.. When using
     -fbaserel the linking fails.. If anyone know why these things happen,
     please tell me! :)

 @{u}Version 1.2@{uu}

   Release date: 16 Mars 1995

   Ę When checking if all parents of an assign had been assigned, there was
     no check for failed assigns. This could cause infinite loops.

   Ę BindNamesII now ignores any icons (files ending with ".info") in the
     names drawer.

 @{u}Version 1.3@{uu}

   Release date: 16 September 1995

   Ę Added the special @{"CMDPATH" Link NAME} assign. That is, you can now also specify
     the command search path with BindNamesII.

   Ę Added the @{"PRIORITY" Link PRIORITY} argument for the targets.

   Ę General code cleanup. Especially the DoPathAdd() function was greatly
     simplified.

   Ę Updated error messages, to show the correct program name. ;)

   Ę Minor typos fixed in this manual.

@EndNode
